Arrau’s desert island recordings:
1. Schubert’s 9th Symphony (Furtwangler)
2. Scheherazade Ravel La Flute Enchantee (Jennie Tourel)
3. Goyescas Granados Los Requiebros (Alicia de Larrocha)
4. Piano Concerto No 2 Saint-Saens (Emil Gilels)
5. Erwartung Schoenberg (Metropolis)
6. Die junge Nonne Schubert (Schwarzkopf + Fischer)
7. Sonata A major D. 959 Schubert (Schnabel)
8. String Quartet No 15 Op 132 Third Movement “Heiliger Dankgesang”Beethoven ( ?? Quartet)

If required to select only one of these eight, Arrau said he would have chosen Furtwangler’s interpretation of Schubert’s Ninth.

Enoch Powell’s desert island recordings:
1. Entry of the Gods into Valhalla from Das Rheingold (Solti)
2. Spring Song from Die Walkure (Solti)
3. Forging Song from Siegfried (Solti)
4. The Renunciation of Siegfried from Gotterdammerung (Solti)
5. Pastoral Symphony (Bohm)
6. Choral Symphony (Schmidt-Isserstedt)
7. Prisoner's Chorus from Fidelio (Klemperer)
8. In Native Worth and Honour Clad from The Creation (Karajan)

If required to select only one of these eight, Powell said he would have chosen Siegfried's Renunciation. It wasn't clear if he meant the whole pieces or just those excerpts, or if those recordings were his choices.

Piano

Difficult to say, for the past couple months I've been working on left hand pieces due to a right wrist injury. Leopold Godowsky's Suite for Left hand alone, specifically the Sarabande, Sicilienne and Minuet. Brahms' piano arrangement of Bach's Chaconne for left hand alone. Godowsky studies for left hand based on Chopin's etudes op. 10 no. 1, no. 2, no. 9 and op 25. no. 12.
Over the past couple of weeks my right hand has recovered so now I'm working my old regular Bach pieces back into shape: the first couple preludes and fugues of WTC I, especially the fugue in C sharp minor, Busoni's arrangment of the Fugue in E flat from Clavier-Ubung III.
Right now I'm probably going to print out some more WTC pieces.

>>114977475
They sound like they have more of a shoegaze/dream pop influence than gospel or soul (at least that what the guitar parts are telling me; I find the vocals to be very plain without much “soul” in them, for a genre perspective). I don’t hear much country in the violin playing. I do hear quite a bit of King Crimson influence. The reason why they don’t come off as pretentious is because the singer/keyboardist writes songs and the band does full arrangements. I mention Sleepytime because Bent Knee used to open for them back in the day, but Sleepytime think more conceptually, have greater influence from bands like Henry Cow and Meshuggah, as well as experiment with found sound percussion in an innovative way.

I dunno, I respect Bent Knee but they don’t do much for me emotionally. I get more excitement from dissonant prog.

>>114979650
I think Yes, King Crimson, and Genesis are great bands, and I think prog is a very interesting impulse, basically taking the next logical step with art rock - if rock could be more ambitious, how far could you push that?

However, those long prog tracks, often done like operas or classical movements, often became a bit of a mess. Pink Floyd kept things clear, simple, and strong, and they were great songwriters. I would say they're the best of those bands, probably. From DSotM on, they always stayed a bit grounded, with focused, strong songs that took on huge topics.

Syd Barrett was such an interesting, surreal songwriter, and that era is a joy to listen to.

Pink Floyd's most interesting period, though, is probably the space rock that came before DSotM, because that's the furthest out they got.

If I had to go for something prog, though, I'd probably go for Can.

Prog was maybe the first step toward what would eventually become post-rock.

but his trumpet playing is pretty tasteful and clever. i'm not saying he's better than coltrane, but conceptually the things he plays aren't simple or low effort or anything like that, despite not being flashy and hard technically. he gives a lot of importance to maintaining the style/vibe of his music so that means not breaking that with things that don't really fit. coltrane does that by having invented his own soloing language so you never think "why is there bebop in my cool jazz?", it just sounds like coltrane, and he's tasteful with it himself anyways. miles achieved sort of the same thing in a different way, instead of replacing the existing jazz vocabulary with super fast stuff and repeating patterns, he replaced it with super slow stuff focusing on building up to and hitting the right notes. and i think it works, i can't identify many things that he's doing, and yet it still magically carries the type of cool jazz that he was doing at the time. he only looks bad because he's next to john fucking coltrane.

All their stuff is really good. You know you'll have truly "got" them once you're picking thru their live shows.

posts.com:
Elderfag here with a Flaming Lips story. 1984-ish, the Lips were playing the Theater Gallery in Dallas in the heart of what would later become the Deep Ellum club area. My friends and I got there early, like, when it was still daylight; had a few beers, hung at the bar.

Wayne Coyne appeared and ordered a drink, iirc it was a Tanqueray and Sprite. He was quite cordial and as the conversation progressed we told him we had some GREAT weed on us.

He invited us backstage, which, to be honest we could have just wandered back there, the Theater Gallery wasn't a huge venue or anything. Still, Wayne had a full "backstage" setup going on, several skulls with candles in them, incense burning, arty tapestries over the bare walls, total stoner scene.

We smoked some weed with the Lips and they told us stories of the road and it was a great time that I will always remember, really on-point guys the Lips, secure in their identities and very talented, optimistic, charismatic, outgoing, the best people in the world to hang with for an hour.

No.
If you are in a major key then the chords would be I ii iii . So for C major this is C major, D minor, E minor. The chords that are in a certain key are made up from the notes in the scale.

In C major the 2,3,4 chords would be ii iii IV, or D minor, E minor, F major.

So even if you used the right capitalization of major/minors in your question the answer is still no because I-ii-iii is a different pattern of major and minor chords than ii-iii-IV

I forgot to write "Minor" but you get the idea, or maybe not.
The C is the white note left of the 2 black keys.
so the C scale goes C D E F G A B C...

you can make chords out of the scale by picking 3 notes that have a note in between, so like C E G, or D F A.
Then when you look at the keyboard you can count how many notes are between those. so for C and E there are 4 "steps" you take from C to E, and 3 steps from E to G

>>114960951
There is a whole step (or 2 steps) between the I, II, and III of a major scale. e.g. C D E all have a black note in between.
II III IV would be a whole step then a half step, like D E F have a black note between D and E but not between E and F
so even though the chords are all major they would not be using the same pattern of root notes unless you are in a weird scale like whole tone or something.

-Beautiful Melodies/catchiness

-Amazing album art

What more could you ask for?

>>114980790
I've listened to every Animal Collective in full many times, and have done so for probably the majority of your life. Strawberry Jam is good, but it's one of their weakest albums of that era. Also, cohesion isn't everything. I like albums that color outside the lines.
>You'll probably appreciate it more when you've gotten to the age they were when they recorded it and you're contemplating the issues of that stage of life.
You seem to be under the impression that I didn't get it. It's a great album and I've listened to it many times, but Feels is still their best album. It's actually their most mature album although it was recorded earlier, because it was such a heavy time for them. Panda Bear and Avey Tare both got married around that time, and Deakin and Geologist just returned for the first time since Here Comes the Indian, so there was a lot of emotion that went into that album. It's also rumored that Deakin had an affair with Kria Brekkan, which led to him leaving again after Strawberry Jam. I also think that due to touring extensively in with just the two of them before writing Feels, the relationship between Avey Tare and Panda Bear had become so deep that it was borderline homosexual. I don't necessarily think they were gay or even bisexual, but it's hard to work with someone that intimately for that long and not develop more complex emotions for them. All of this went into the writing and recording of Feels, and is audible in the sound of that album. That's why it's such an uncomfortable album. It's a wave of different species of emotions. I don't care that they were younger when they recorded it, maturity is not a linear thing. They broke through to a level that few artists reach with feels. Either way, I'm currently the age that they were when they made Merriweather, so it's not like I'm not old enough to understand their songs. I understood Strawberry Jam ten years ago, but Feels is an album that still gains depth each time I listen to it.

>>114974347
Bowie has several GREAT albums. My favorite is Station To Station but I'm not married to it, I could easily listen to any of his classic-era albums and be edified.

He did have a late-career decline, like many artists do. His albums after Let's Dance tend toward the contrived. Except what he did with Tin Machine, which was excellent.

Still, anything Bowie put out from 1970-1983 is considered all-time classic rock, and rightfully so. Interesting sidenote, unlike most musicians Bowie didn't have a "sophomore slump." His first eponymous release is actually his worst album, after that he simply got better and better, consistently, until Scary Monsters. Bowie was a true artist, I would LOVE to be a musical novice just starting to explore his catalog, great memories, great music.

OP im the same age as you. I just entered high school when MCR / FOB / Hawthorne Heights etc were dominating MTV. As an indie rocker, that stuff wasn't for me. The emo's had their distinct identity, to be an MCR fan in high school meant you had to wear the shirt and have the emo hair etc. - it was a commitment to join that scene. I never listened to an MCR album back then, but the singles were inescapable, and even then, with my elitest p4kcore taste, I had to admit Helena and Im Not Okay were/are fucking brilliant pop songs (along with FOB's Sugar We're Going Down, The Used's Taste Of Ink, AFI Girl's Not Grey, TBS Cute Without The E, even Panic!'s big hit wasn't that bad - there were a number of undeniable emo pop tracks to come out of that era). My friend who was strictly into classic rock and turned up his nose at all the faggoty emo shit going on even agreed with me that props were due to MCR for that guitar solo in Im Not Okay, in an era where guitar solo's were dying out. Now, when Black Parade came out I was far less impressed with those singles and thought the Queenish theatrics were simply gay (still are).

I don't think MCR's current popularity is necessarily all zoomer revisionism. They were beloved by a generation of emos. They were probably the highest profile band of that emo pop movement, and they went hard with the aesthetics. They also quit while they were ahead, unlike FOB who have embarrassed themselves with the Imagine Dragons reinvention. I noticed the nostalgia for MCR already running thick amongst millennials in the mid 10s.

I finally got around to listening to the albums a few years ago. Three Cheers is a fantastic album. No rock bands, mainstream or otherwise, have really come close to making a track as massive as Helena, that is an absolute timeless anthem. Black Parade has some good tracks. I can see why the grandiose theatrical concept album thing appeals to fans of that album but to me the songs just aren't there. reached length limit.

posts.sub: The real reason for the idea that learning theory kills genuine creativity and inspired music
posts.com:
The most basic of the musical structures cataloged and studied in music theory are so intuitive - major scale sound good - that you can apply it without having any explicit grasp of, or education in theory. They are also the most easily applied, and most "efficient", for lack of a better word, means of evoking strong emotion. When a musician learns theory they are tempted to employ ideas outside the most basic and intuitive fundamentally appealing musical structures. These structures are less ingrained in the human mind/perception/consciousness/evolutionary-whatever/nature-of-existnece/whatever-you-think-music-operates-on/in (I make no claims here about the actual ontological state of music, the entities posited by music theoretical concepts, and musical value) and are therefore much harder to use effectively in evoking emotion.

Music theory is just that - theory - a field of research - a project of peering into the dark edges of what we know works, to see what new and exciting things could be done. Unsurprisingly, the results are often not as effective as four chords and Sufjan Stevens whispering simple sweet melodies with evocative lyrics. Once one is educated in some music theory concept, it's tempting to explore the potential of those concepts, rather than sticking to what is the most direct and reliable, even if one knows the results might ultimately be less emotionally effective in some absolute sense. Hence music made by theory laden musicians often being seen as soulless, emotionally middling, purely intellectual, etc. It often is. It's a rare artist who finds a way of employing musical structures outside the most basic, most appealing, most direct, most intuitive ones, in truly effective ways.

posts.com:
>>114982611
It's not hard, it just takes time and patience. It also depends on what you want out of it. You could pick up a guitar and be playing Wonderwall by next weekend, but if you wanted to tackle some Bach fugues on the organ, you could easily be at it for a year or two and still feel hopelessly shit. If you're happy with sing-alongs, learning about progressions alongside how to play chords on a piano or guitar can get you to a point that will impress normies in a matter of months. Maybe even weeks if you're a NEET with nothing better to do.

>>114982678
I think it's more that people don't have the time to put into it, or can't handle the frustration of your hands not doing what you want them to do. Most people probably haven't experienced that type of thing since they were toddlers and have no memory of what it's like. It's not a fun feeling. So they give quit. They find another hobby that gives them the instant gratification they're looking for

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
While Any Colour You Like is instrumental, it has been speculated that the song ties to The Dark Side of the Moon concept by considering the lack of choice one has in human society, while being deluded into thinking one does. It is also speculated that the song is about the fear of making choices. The origin of the title is unclear.

The first half of the song repeats the same few notes on the keyboard except they play it faster, slower, backwards. and forwards to create the illusion of listening to different things. It cleverly shows how people are mislead into thinking they are deciding how their life will run, but that is not the case as society forces you to take a certain path. Note its position on the album, too. "Us and Them" is about paranoia, immediately following this is "Any Colour You Like" and then "Brain Damage", finally Eclipse. Any Colour is the nervous breakdown that comes in between the onset of paranoia and the "brain damage."

The song used advanced effects for the time both in the keyboard and the guitar. The VCS 3 synthesizer was fed through a long tape loop to create the rising and falling keyboard solo. David Gilmour used two guitars with the Uni-Vibe guitar effect to create the harmonizing guitar solo for the rest of the song. "Any Colour You Like" is also known (and is even listed on the Dark Side guitar tablature book) as "Breathe (Second Reprise)" because the song shares the same beat (albeit somewhat funkier and uptempo) as the album's first song "Breathe". It has also nearly the same chord sequence just transposed a whole step lower from E minor to D minor.

The reason why I have fallen in monogamic love with this tune is due to its perfection. The production behind it is unmatchable by any standard. The synthesizers take front row for most of the production, and the guitar/bass/drum combo serve as a base. In my mind, this is what a song should try to achieve if it wants to be perfect.
